In Vue 2, you can define the `click` event for a button using the `v-on` directive. Here is an example of how to define the `click` event for a button in Vue 2:

```
<template>
  <button v-on:click="handleClick">Click me</button>
</template>

<script>
export default {
  methods: {
    handleClick() {
      // Do something when the button is clicked
      console.log("Button clicked!");
    }
  }
}
</script>
```

In this example, the `v-on:click` directive is used to define the `click` event for the button. When the button is clicked, the `handleClick` method is called. Inside the `handleClick` method, you can perform any logic or operations you want.

You can also use the shorthand syntax `@click` instead of `v-on:click`, like this:

```
<template>
  <button @click="handleClick">Click me</button>
</template>

<!-- rest of the code -->
```

Both `v-on:click` and `@click` are interchangeable and will produce the same result.

To add an `onclick` event to a `PopoverTrigger` component in Vue 2, you can use the `v-on` or `@` directive and specify the `click` event.

Here's an example of how you can add an `onclick` event to a `PopoverTrigger` component in Vue 2:

```vue
<template>
  <PopoverTrigger>
    <button @click="openPopover">Open Popover</button>
    <Popover>
      <!-- Popover content -->
    </Popover>
  </PopoverTrigger>
</template>

<script>
  export default {
    methods: {
      openPopover() {
        // Do something when the button is clicked
        console.log("Popover opened!");
      }
    }
  }
</script>
```

In this example, we are using the `PopoverTrigger` component to create a button that triggers a popover when clicked. The `@click` directive is used to add the `onclick` event to the button, and the `openPopover` method is called when the button is clicked.

You can adjust the `openPopover` method according to your requirements and perform any logic or operations you need.
